results.response_preview: The internet began in the 1960s as ARPANET, a U.S. Department of Defense project designed to create a decentralized communication network that could survive nuclear attacks. This revolutionary system connected four computers in 1969, establishing packet-switching technology that became the foundation for modern networking. Throughout the 1970s and 1980s, the network expanded to universities and research institutions, while Tim Berners-Lee invented the World Wide Web in 1989, introducing HTTP protocols and HTML that made information easily accessible through browsers.  The 1990s marked the internet's commercialization and explosive growth. The first web browser, Mosaic, launched in 1993, followed by Netscape and Internet Explorer. E-commerce emerged with Amazon and eBay, while email became mainstream communication. The dot-com boom of the late 1990s saw massive investment in internet companies, though many failed during the 2001 crash. Broadband replaced dial-up connections, enabling faster data transmission and richer multimedia content.  By 2030, the internet will likely be dominated by artificial intelligence integration, quantum computing networks, and ubiquitous connectivity through 6G technology, fundamentally transforming human interaction.
results.full_response:
The internet began in the 1960s as ARPANET, a U.S. Department of Defense project designed to create a decentralized communication network that could survive nuclear attacks. This revolutionary system connected four computers in 1969, establishing packet-switching technology that became the foundation for modern networking. Throughout the 1970s and 1980s, the network expanded to universities and research institutions, while Tim Berners-Lee invented the World Wide Web in 1989, introducing HTTP protocols and HTML that made information easily accessible through browsers.

The 1990s marked the internet's commercialization and explosive growth. The first web browser, Mosaic, launched in 1993, followed by Netscape and Internet Explorer. E-commerce emerged with Amazon and eBay, while email became mainstream communication. The dot-com boom of the late 1990s saw massive investment in internet companies, though many failed during the 2001 crash. Broadband replaced dial-up connections, enabling faster data transmission and richer multimedia content.

By 2030, the internet will likely be dominated by artificial intelligence integration, quantum computing networks, and ubiquitous connectivity through 6G technology, fundamentally transforming human interaction.
